quran[7]{c,v,t,f}:
  101,10,"And what do you know what that is?"
  101,11,"A Blazing Fire!{1}",footnotes:1:That is, it will not merely be a deep pit but will also be full of raging fire.
  102,7,"again, you shall most certainly end up seeing it with absolute certainty."
  102,8,"Then, on that Day, you will be called to account for all the bounties you enjoyed.{1}",footnotes:1:“Then” in this sentence does not mean that accountability will be held after the culprits have been cast into Hell, but it means: Then We give you the news that you will be questioned about these comforts of life, and obviously this questioning will be held at the time of accountability in the divine court. Its main argument is that in several Ahadith it has been reported from the Prophet (peace be upon him) that the believers and the disbelievers, both will have to account for the blessings granted by Allah. However, the people who did not show ingratitude but spent their lives as grateful servants of Allah, will come out successful from the accountability, and those who proved thankless to Allah for His blessings and committed ingratitude by word or by deed, or by both; will emerge as failures.
  104,1,"Woe to every fault-finding backbiter;{1}",footnotes:1:The words used in the original are humazat il-lumazah.
  104,2,"who amasses wealth and counts it over and again.{1}",footnotes:1:This second sentence after the first sentence by itself
  104,3,"He thinks that his wealth will immortalise him forever.{1}",footnotes:1:Another meaning also can be: He thinks that his wealth